  <!-- METHODS -->
  <section id="methods">
    <div class="section-header">
      <span class="section-num">01</span>
      <h2 class="section-title">Methodology</h2>
    </div>

    <!-- Pipeline Flow -->
    <p style="font-family:var(--mono); font-size:0.72rem; letter-spacing:0.1em; text-transform:uppercase; color:var(--muted); margin-bottom:1rem;">Analysis Pipeline</p>
    <div class="pipeline">
      <div class="pipe-step">Raw Data</div>
      <span class="pipe-arrow">→</span>
      <div class="pipe-step">EDA</div>
      <span class="pipe-arrow">→</span>
      <div class="pipe-step">Feature Engineering</div>
      <span class="pipe-arrow">→</span>
      <div class="pipe-step">Interaction Testing</div>
      <span class="pipe-arrow">→</span>
      <div class="pipe-step active">Model Training</div>
      <span class="pipe-arrow">→</span>
      <div class="pipe-step">CV Threshold Tuning</div>
      <span class="pipe-arrow">→</span>
      <div class="pipe-step">Bias Audit</div>
    </div>

    <div class="methods-grid" style="margin-top:2rem;">
      <div class="method-card">
        <div class="method-icon">🌲</div>
        <div class="method-name">Decision-Tree Binning</div>
        <div class="method-desc">Credit scores were binned using information-gain splits (entropy criterion, max 5 leaves), producing four interpretable tiers: Poor, Low, Moderate, High.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="method-card">
        <div class="method-icon">📐</div>
        <div class="method-name">Interaction Testing</div>
        <div class="method-desc">Likelihood ratio tests and AIC/BIC comparisons evaluated five candidate interaction terms. Two were retained: Debt × Moderate Credit Score and YearsEmployed × log(Income).</div>
      </div>
      <div class="method-card">
        <div class="method-icon">🎯</div>
        <div class="method-name">CV Threshold Optimization</div>
        <div class="method-desc">Out-of-fold predicted probabilities from stratified 5-fold CV were used to select the threshold maximizing F-beta (β=2), preventing test-set leakage.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="method-card">
        <div class="method-icon">🔬</div>
        <div class="method-name">SHAP Explainability</div>
        <div class="method-desc">SHAP values were computed for the tuned Random Forest to explain global feature importance and individual prediction drivers beyond standard permutation importance.</div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <div class="divider"><hr /></div>

  <!-- EDA FINDINGS -->
  <section id="eda">
    <div class="section-header">
      <span class="section-num">02</span>
      <h2 class="section-title">EDA Key Findings</h2>
    </div>
    <div class="findings-list">
      <div class="finding-item">
        <span class="finding-tag green">Top Predictor</span>
        <p class="finding-text">
          <strong>Prior default history</strong> is the single strongest predictor of approval outcomes (|r| ≈ 0.72 with approval).
          Applicants with a prior default are rejected at dramatically higher rates — a finding consistent across descriptive,
          regression, and tree-based models.
        </p>
      </div>
      <div class="finding-item">
        <span class="finding-tag green">Financial Stability</span>
        <p class="finding-text">
          <strong>Employment status and tenure</strong> were the second and third strongest predictors. Employed applicants
          convert at substantially higher rates, and each additional year employed improves approval probability independently.
          Credit score (|r| ≈ 0.41) and income also showed strong positive associations.
        </p>
      </div>
      <div class="finding-item">
        <span class="finding-tag blue">Feature Engineering</span>
        <p class="finding-text">
          Income was <strong>log-transformed</strong> to reduce right skew (skew reduced from ~3.9 to ~0.6).
          Credit scores were binned into four tiers using decision-tree information gain, improving interpretability
          while preserving predictive structure. ZipCode was dropped due to extreme overfitting risk (170 unique values).
        </p>
      </div>
      <div class="finding-item">
        <span class="finding-tag blue">Interactions</span>
        <p class="finding-text">
          Two interaction terms were retained after LR tests: <strong>Debt × Moderate Credit Score</strong> (p &lt; 0.01,
          AIC improved by ~6 points) and <strong>YearsEmployed × log(Income)</strong> (p ≈ 0.03). Three others —
          Debt×Income, CreditScore×Income, PriorDefault×CreditScore — were dropped due to non-significance,
          limited AIC gains, or model convergence failure.
        </p>
      </div>
      <div class="finding-item">
        <span class="finding-tag">Demographics</span>
        <p class="finding-text">
          Demographic variables (age, gender, marital status, citizenship) were dropped after EDA — they showed
          weak independent relationships with approval and introduced bias risk. <strong>Industry and ethnicity</strong>
          were retained as dummy variables to allow controlled analysis of group-level disparities.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <div class="divider"><hr /></div>

