  <!-- BIAS ANALYSIS -->
  <section id="bias">
    <div class="section-header">
      <span class="section-num">04</span>
      <h2 class="section-title">Bias Analysis</h2>
    </div>
    <p style="color:var(--muted); font-size:0.95rem; max-width:640px; margin-bottom:1.5rem;">
      Approval outcomes were examined across demographic groups and employment sectors to identify potential disparities and test whether they persist after controlling for financial characteristics.
    </p>

    <div class="findings-list">
      <div class="finding-item">
        <span class="finding-tag red">Disparity</span>
        <p class="finding-text">
          Latino applicants in the dataset were approved at approximately <span class="hl">14%</span>,
          compared to <strong>42–63%</strong> for other ethnic groups — a substantial raw gap.
          Latino applicants also exhibited higher prior default rates, lower income, and fewer years of
          employment, which are known approval drivers.
        </p>
      </div>
      <div class="finding-item">
        <span class="finding-tag red">Controlled Result</span>
        <p class="finding-text">
          After controlling for all financial predictors (debt, income, employment, prior default, credit
          score, bank status), the Latino ethnicity coefficient remained <strong>statistically significant
          at the 5% level</strong>, with approximately a <strong>75% lower odds of approval</strong>.
          However, the Latino subsample contains only <span class="hl">57 individuals</span>, raising
          caution about estimate stability and generalizability.
        </p>
      </div>
      <div class="finding-item">
        <span class="finding-tag blue">Industry</span>
        <p class="finding-text">
          Approval rates varied widely by industry: Utilities (~84%) and IT (~71%) at the top;
          Healthcare (~13%) and Real Estate (~23%) at the bottom. A controlled regression found
          that <strong>most industry effects disappeared</strong> after accounting for financial profiles —
          lower-approval industries tended to have higher prior default rates and weaker credit characteristics.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

